This place will steal your money if you try to pay with your card inside!!!!! They got me for $9.99 after telling me my card was declined and to run it as credit (which was also declined). However, at the pump, my card worked just fine. When i noticed my pending transactions later that same day, i returned to the store and tried talking to the employee who had helped me. She started ranting and raving that I was out to get her when i asked to see the copies of both declined receipts as she had only given me one. She then proceeded to take the reeceipts out laying them down one by one. Right before the decline which i had a copy for, i noticed the previous receipt was for $9.99. I asked to see the receipt to make sure it wasn't an accidental charge and this employee flipped out. I will never go here again. A few months back the same incident happened to my roommate, same gas station but different employee. They got her for $30. It seems that this is acceptable employee practices and behavior to this Valero owner, shame on you!!!!!<//review>

<Review>We have stayed in four Avalon properties in the bay area over 5 years, but Eaves Creekside is the absolutely the worst property and a huge disappointment. Besides the property being extremely old (built in 1970s) and lacking some key facilities (EV charging, air conditioning, hot tub etc.), we want to share the four real stories happened to us during this year for your reference:

1. The building is SO old and poorly maintained that the roof broke and rain water flooded everywhere during our stay! :((  See photos of our place attached. Our entire floor was wet, our carpet soaked in water, the furniture damaged by the flood, and the wall was all brown. It turned out that there was a hole in the roof that was not properly fixed before this unit was rented out. The weeks following the incident, we had to live in construction noise every day and wait for the mess to be cleaned up.

What made us most angry was that after all these terrible things happened, the building management just told us "Hey this could happen to anyone. You can use your renters' insurance." No reimbursement, no quick fix-up (it took weeks end to end), and no responses to our emails for days. It took many emails, phone calls, in-person meetings to get the situation barely fixed and only a few days of rent concessions back, despite all the disruptions to our life.

2. We kept have personal valuables stolen in the complex. I parked and locked my $400 bike with TWO locks in my building under the staircase. First it was a ring bell and a bike light missing (I should have acted right then, now thinking back), and then my whole bike including the locks were gone!

It turned out this complex is very unsafe and full of theft risks. My neighbor later shared that they had their bike locked on the second floor balcony also stolen last year! Just take a walk in the complex - if you look carefully around the bike stations, you will see a couple of bikes with stolen seats, wheels etc. parked here and there. No wonder the vacancy rate is so here in this complex right now.

3. A lot of huge BUGs in your apartments! Starting from April, we spotted many bugs large and small in our apartment frequently (2-3/week). Some silver giant flies are as big as my thumb and SO disgusting!! The exterminator had to came and he mentioned that these bugs happen a lot in the apartment complex. They are caused by dead mouse nearby apparently :((.

4. Unresponsive sloppy management. What kind of management takes 4 weeks to respond to a renewal request, when it is only 2 weeks before the lease end? First they started with a ridiculous renewing price that is way above the market (>20% more than the most expensive, exact same alternative units in the complex). Then when we asked for a short-term renewal price (to just bridge some personal plan during COVID), we had to email, call, and visit the office at least 10 times in the past 4 weeks to get some clarify on our options, but still we have no concrete answer back. It turned out the original manager just left the property and no proper transition was made then. As a result, the new managers in office are swamped.

All in all, I have to say that I am supremely disappointed by our experience here. We had high hopes when we moved here from all the past good ones with Avalon. Unfortunately this particular place just does not live up to the reputation. I would recommend you look elsewhere because this property does not do Mountain View, a cute town the justice.

I would also implore Avalon corporate to look into the operations at this particular property. If our stories are not enough, the high vacancy rate here is a very telling sign.<//Review>< Gmap_id>

<Review>I lived at eaves Creekside in a tiny studio (<200 sq. ft.) for which I paid 2050$ monthly (with no utilities included).
TL;DR: Overpriced and inefficient; lots of maintenance issues but good maintenance folks

Cons:
- Maintenance issues
A. The toilet over-flooding: Because of plumbing issues at someone else's apartment, I had come home one day to have water all over my place.
B. The laundry card not working: I spent countless hours over weekends on getting my laundry card filled and working; the laundry room machines were extremely dysfunctional. Often I had to call the card contract company and show them evidence that I had put money in.
C. The main closet door being wiggly: At one point I was afraid the door would fall on me while I was asleep given there was so little space.

- Attitude of management / moving out
The office staff wasn't as cooperative as I would have liked, given how pricey this place is. I had to break my lease because I was moving jobs ~9 months in. The lease breaking fees seemed quite high even with a month notice, and there was no easy provision for lease transfer. Given this is Silicon Valley where people often change jobs, one would expect moving out to be smoother, cheaper and efficient. But this seemed highly monopolistic.

- Apartment
For an apartment this tiny, one would ideally expect to have a decent window. My apartment had a window-like thing high up, close to the ceiling. Unless the front door was open, the place felt like a prison cell.

- Heating / energy efficiency
I ended up paying >200$ a month on heating, which seemed high for an apartment this tiny (<200 sqft), given this is not a particularly cold city. I believe this is because there was high heat dissipation from the apartment.

Pros:
- The maintenance folks were friendly, quick and efficient, so kudos to them.
- The apartment complex is located ten minutes walk from Downtown Mountain View.</Review><Date>1616455339420</Date><user>111176896389698426895< /user>< Pictures>

< Text>
Honestly not a bad place to live. My lease was for one year and I had a single bedroom unit. The price was astronomical high (but fair for the area). The amenities are decent (small, but equipped gym and a clubhouse with pools and grills), but nothing to write home about. The place was clean, but a bit old and run down (even after the recent renovations). One major complaint I had was the paper thin walls/floors. I could easily hear my neighbors moving around or talking. Good thing my neighbors were relatively quiet for the most part. Also, I wanted to move one month before my lease expiration and the leasing office would not negotiate. Not a big deal, but worth mentioning. The area around the complex is nice with easy access to all major South Bay freeways, Caltrain, a few walking trails and of course downtown Mountain View. Overall a pleasant experience for a first time renter and after moving cross-country!</Text>

I have lived here for just under one year and have had a wonderful experience. The on-site managers, especially Sam and Linda, have been so accommodating and helpful.

When I had a tree removal in-front of my unit they were very apologetic and upfront with everything..and even gave me a rent cut for that month!

The pool was my go-to workout cool down. On a hot day after a long run on the near by Steven's Creek Trail or after a good workout in the newly renovated gym, I would jump in one of the three pools to cool down. One of the pools has a clubhouse with pool table in it which i regularly had people over for a day of hanging out by the pool with some cold beverages.

The few times I had to call for maintenance, they were there within 24hrs to take care of the issue.

I was very lucky to have super quiet neighbors, some good natural light (in the afternoon when I got home from work), and a corner unit on the first floor! It was definitely a great apartment.

This is definitely the ideal place to live if you are looking for a place in Mountain View.

I unfortunately have to move to a new location - I was offered a job in a different city. When I went to the leasing office to explain this, they were extremely understanding and have offered to help me rent the apartment for the remainder of our lease.

I will soon update this review post-move-out to let you know how my time at Eaves finished off!

UPDATE***
This is an update from my past review. Linda at the leasing office had my apartment leased for me just as she promised within two days of moving out! This saved me tons of money. I HIGHLY recommend Eaves Creekside to anyone and everyone moving to Mountain View.<//Review>

<Rating>4<//Rating><Text>While the apartments themselves are not much to write about the community has been wonderful, the location is great, and the management and maintenance staff have been very helpful.  There are a lot of friendly late 20's to early 30's professionals here.  Many people have dogs and there is even a dog park on the property.  There are multiple swimming pools, a pair of tennis courts, and a BBQ area in addition.  Guest parking usually isn't too hard to find.

Right by the apartment is the Steven's Creek Trail, which if you work on or near the Google campus is a great benefit.  A couple blocks away is downtown Mountain View so bars, liquor stores, and restaurants are a quick walk away.

The staff have been very helpful and even opened the leasing office early for me to come in and sign my lease before I had to bee at work.  All of my maintenance requests have been answered the same day, and when I was locked out of my apartment one night at 2 A.M. someone was there within 20 minutes to let me in.

The apartments themselves are not very special.  They are large enough, though fairly old.  They are starting to remodel some of them, and I can't speak to those, but the older ones only have two-prong electrical outlets and older appliances (fridge, garbage disposal, dishwasher, oven, and stove).  There is asbestos in the walls, but only in the joining tape, so unless you plan on knocking down the walls (which you shouldn't be doing anyway) this shouldn't be a problem.  The only big downside to living here is the price, which goes way up for short term leases (however, this seems to be the case for most places around here).  All in all I would recommend this place if you have the money and need a dog friendly environment.<//Text>< Pictures>

< review>
I've lived hear about a year and a half and I'm pretty happy overall. It's a little expensive (what in this area is actually priced reasonably though?) and slightly older, but the apartment itself is relatively nice. I haven't had to contact maintenance once. The grounds are well kept and there are pools and a fitness center and other amenities. My primary complaint is that the walls must be slightly thin (I think that's probably par for the course around here though--and they're not paper thin). All my neighbors are fairly quiet so it's not a problem generally and normal conversation is not audible, but there's one guy below me or next to me who must snore like a freight train and I occasionally hear it at night (I use the sound of a box fan to drown him out or my air conditioner (not included) in the summer). The location is fantastic though--short walk to downtown and to the caltrain, plus there's an entrance to the Stevens Creek Trail at the back of the apartment (which is great for taking a bike ride or a run on).

Overall, no real regrets moving here.

Update: 8/11/18 (2.5 years living here)

I had one negative incident where maintenance came into my apartment unannounced and worked on the bathroom fan and left a little dirt in my bathroom but, more importantly, inadvertently let my new kitten (aside: the pet rent is a bit pricey) into an area that was not safe for him! I spoke to the manager and she was apologetic and said she'd look into why I wasn't notified. I was frustrated, but I haven't had any other negative experiences, so I don't think this is a pattern but it was not positive.

My disposal jammed last month and I called maintenance to have it unjammed twice, and on both occasions service came quickly and resolved the problem. They said if it happens again they'll probably replace it, but it's been working for a few weeks now.

My overall original impression stands though. It's not perfect, but I'm generally satisfied.</review>

< review>
Overall, its been amazing for the 1 week that we've been here for. Ruben has been helping us through our move in, and is doing an amazing job! Makes sure we are comfortable every time we see him, and makes sure he deals with our requests in a timely manner. Thanks, Ruben!

I also want to comment on the excellent services of the maintenance team, especially Christian!

There are some concerns that we had about how quickly rents change here (more than other apartments) but that's something we are going to be careful about in the future.

The only other major criticism I have is about the construction of the apartment in that we can hear our 1st floor neighbours (we are on the 2nd floor) and I know they can hear us too. The flooring is very wobbly and when we walk - the apartment rambles!< /review>

<Resp>None</Resp>< Review>
I moved here from Minnesota in May 2012.  I had little time to coordinate a move (I work for the government).  I had friends out here already, and one of them went to check it out.  They said it was ok.  I actually had to sign the lease without ever actually seeing the place until I arrived at the property the day I physically moved in.

Management from the beginning was very helpful.  Every question I had, they answered to the best of their ability.  When I put in maintenance requests, they are promptly addressed.  The property and community have been absolutely fantastic.  I'm very happy living here--it's a great area.

It IS quite expensive.  I assume it's because of it's location and how high demand this particular area is.  Also, Santa Clara County DOES NOT have rent controls.  Which is both good and bad.  Good because it keeps the garbage out, bad because if you don't have the cash, your stay here could be short term.

I do very much recommend living here though if you can afford it.  You could definitely do a lot worse!  The apartments are old, but large enough to not be horribly cramped.  I have a 1 bedroom and it suits my needs just fine.</Review>

111141679880639298629< /userid>
<Name>Z Jin<//Name><Time>1438382928932< /Time><Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
When it comes to finding an excellent apartment in the silicon valley/Stanford area, my No. 1 recommendation is and will always be Eaves Creekside, Mountain View. We as a family lived there, 151 Calderon Avenue, for almost eleven months, and we just love the place. I lived in the United States for, off and on, almost eight years. This is the only place that makes me feel like home.

First, the management team is super nice! They treat you like a family. They can remember your name and apartment number. Whenever I went to the front desk for a mail-delivered package, they would get it right away with a smile on the face, without asking the routine question: What is your apartment number?

They fix issues in the apartment in a very efficient and professional manner. Just a simple call, they would come to your apartment within a couple of hours and get things done. I once operated the heater incorrectly and the safety switch for the heating was automatically shut off. The technical repair guy came to my apartment and within merely seconds fixed the issue by pushing a red button, the safety switch, on the upper left corner of the heater. They really know things well. The other time the light under the ceiling fan went out, and again within a couple of hours, the issue got fixed and a new light bulb was installed.

They could also help you out on things that have nothing to do with them. Once I had the plastic part at the lower front part of my car fall off by hitting a ditch somewhere. I was thinking about taking this issue to a car mechanical shop. I just chatted about this at the front desk. There was a management team member who knew a lot about cars. He was able to put the plastic part back to the original position immediately. Another time I lost an expected mail. They contacted the post office, did the job for me, and got my mail back.

We had to terminate the lease one month in advance because of visa issues. We thought we had to fulfill the contract by paying for the remaining period of the time. But we guessed wrong. A couple of weeks after we notified them of our intention to move out of the apartment and get back to our home country, they had already found the next tenant who wished to move in right after our move out date. So we saved one month‚Äôs rent.

The Eaves Creekside complex has all the facilities you can imagine to exercise your body: swimming pool, gym, tennis court, basketball court, etc.

Of course, the second reason is the location. The place is very close to Caltrain station. Do not underestimate the importance of that. Even though we had a car, we often took the Caltrain when sometimes we did not want to drive (for example, going to San Francisco). The place is also very close to downtown Mountain View. That allowed us to taste cuisines from different countries by simply walking to the Castro street: Mediterranean, French, Italian, Indian, Chinese, Japanese, Thai, Vietnamese, etc. Yes, you can drink beer and wine and walk back home. That is nice! Castro street is part of the reason why we could enjoy our stay in the United States without getting bored. The place is also very close to highways: 237, 85, 101. That can save you a lot of time without having to drive on local roads, especially during rush hours.

Overall, I think Eaves Creekside is the No. 1 choice for those working or studying in the silicon valley/Stanford area. I will live here again if I have a chance to move back to this area in the future.<//text>

I ordered the lava cake topped with vanilla ice cream plus a hot tea with cream and casey ordered a cake ice cream shake.  none came with icecream.  it was all liquidy melted goop. my tea came no cream.  so i had to wait. casey starving are and gulped down the slimy like shake. the waiter came back no cresm, i had nibbled my cake after scooping the glop off it and showed him the ooze mess... the waiter was told about the ice cream being NOT anything resembling ice cream and he mentioned the freezer never completely froze the ice cream and it was always like that and left i thought to go get my cream. Casey had multiple sclerosis and had to leave paid bill while leaving me to wait for cream.  i asked new waitress for hot water and to go cup my tea was untouched and now frozen better than the icecream. i asked for a new tea bag since i paid for hot tea and was told i had to pay for it i said i paid for a hot tea and havent gotten it yet because i was waiting on my cream. she refused to give me one. i started getting very upset because these people didnt care aboit customer service or health hazards or if consumers got sick off of their unhealthy service of hazardous foods. so i asked to speak to manager, claudia came out and literally told me well it looks like you ate everything. i said no heres my ice cream on the side, and two bites out of cake, the shake had been gulped down but it wasnt good. i asked for refund. she refused. i said here is the cold tea i havent drank because i had no cream. she said id have to pay dor another tea bag. i said seriously? i took one look at her and realized she was either drunk or high and there is no way she was going to get that the service sucked and the product was not worth the price we paid. i took ny ticket and left . This place is dirty, has a sewer odor and the staff just dont care about anything. this place should be inspected by the health department and should probably be shut down. they should also be taken to court for false advertising. this is not even remotely close to a typical Dennys restaurant. I hope Corporate Dennys sees this and other complaints and strips this franchise out of the franchiseslum owners hands or the Corporate office should shut this location down. because it is an awful, disgusting example of Dennys restaurant chain.< /text>< pictures>

<pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN6fe7wLUDq-1kC5P4yrEpWTNWgWi8AiJvQRQE=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO4CySdjgUhGx549Jox5Tb8k6C8K_jdpLxzLeY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPHlOHIOjpIWyVUO1yvyuhRfKxytD05eiXRrHk=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><user>104787723895919552128<//user>< rate>
5</rate>
<username>Jeff Hanlen</username><Time>1572389616886< /Time>< text>
Enjoy that "South of the Border" taste - without being South of the Border! This is a great little eatery with a diverse range of ingredients. Beef, pork, seafood - and also vegan options (the cactus taco is an experience). We tried the spicy shrimp, cactus and the pork offerings, and each of them were incredibly tasty and satisfying.
Service is prompt and friendly, with a range of beer and non-alcoholic options available. Seating is generous-but-cozy, both inside and outside (which is perfect when the sun is shining down on your table.) The atmosphere is definitely family-friendly, and the outside area even lends itself to bringing along your dog to envy the experience.
Some lovely home-style salsas and dips are available to tease the tastebuds and scorch the throat. As a side-dish, do not miss the corn on the cob (covered in cheese and ready for a squeeze of lime).
Highly recommended if you're in the mood for some authentic and creative Mexican fare.<//text>

<Rate>4</Rate>< Review>
High quality Mexican food in a casual atmosphere. Our favorites are the Sonora Taco, Mar y Tierra Burrito, and the Mexican corn on the cob. This place serves angus beef, no joke. The location is on Encinitas Blvd next to shops and a couple of blocks from the beach. So you can always go for a walk after enjoying a delicious meal. The only reason why I did not give this place 5 stars is because during the pandemic the gentleman from whom you pick up your food is really rude, he needs customer service training. Other than that I found all other employees to be kind and helpful. There is always a line to get in, so patience is required.< /Review>

<userid>106813724666609302606</userid>< Time>
1583187062623</Time>
< pics>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP3cVJUXlHbSnjjvasq8QSjIYQlriIeUHwH3F0E=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNb6giruJbwQhJeyp_2SbqlUEBSyXItKjTPwb5O=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>
<text>I've never been to Mexico so I don't have a baseline for a real street taco. However, one free Tuesday, my wife and I took a Lyft and got dropped off at Fish 101 in Leucadia. We got 3 mahi tacos there for $12 and a $3 Baja taco. I wasn't impressed. We walked down the highway into the next stop, at Juanita's Taco shop. I got a Baja taco there and I liked it. But I was still hungering for a good fish taco. We were pretty stuffed after about 5 tacos in. But then we found the Taco Stand.

There, we ordered. There, we ate. There, we returned.
My wife and I ate here three times in 24 hours. We had their Baja taco, their carne asada, their al pastor, their camaron. We also had their carne asada burrito, corn on the cob, and hot churros. Forgive me for these low quality photos of high quality food. I just couldn't wait to eat the food right after I could smell them. The corn was so nostalgic of my childhood. The churros made me scared of stepping into the scale for my doctor's appointment the week after.  The tacos made me want to renew my passport so I could enter Mexico.

However, we had their horchata and Jamaica juice, and we both thought that they were a little too watered down. It may have just been that day, but oh well :(. I've had really good horchatas, but theirs that day was not the best.

They also make their tortillas in house. Overall, the taco stand have earned their spot in my heart.<//text></record>

< text>
5 stars for great Mexican food, definitely not as greasy as many spots (which I am conflicted on is actually a good thing) but nonetheless the taco stand has an excellent menu with great quality ingredients. This is one of the few places where I always know if I order something with fish or shrimp it will be fresh & worth it... Mar y tierra fries areüî•. Not something I can say of all places with the same price points.

There is almost always a longggg line but I don't feel it's worth deducting a star on this review of the establishment because that's more of a rating of the ppl in Encinitas haha but if you go be willing to wait it's likely worth it.

During the quarantine grabbing food to go a few days ago was the best customer service experience I've had here. The girl at the counter was nice, got the correct order & also misspelled my name "Melo" which reminds me of Carmelo Anthony so I did not take offense. You're doing great if you read this.<//text>

< Text>
I came here with a friend who has been meaning to check this place out and I am so thankful.

I ordered the guacamole with chips, two al pastor tacos, horchata, and churros.

Everything was amazing!! The tacos were flavorful, the salsas were refreshing, and the churros with the sweetened condensed milk was the best way to end the meal. The guacamole was great - lots of avocado and fresh cilantro and lime.

Parking can be tough so don‚Äôt be disgruntled you can‚Äôt find something right away, this place is worth it. Note: the churros were the first thing to come out (since they bring your meals to the table when it‚Äôs ready). If you don‚Äôt want them right away, I‚Äôd recommend going back up to order them.< /Text>

<name>J J<//name>< Time>
1579064560210</Time>
<Rating>4< /Rating>< text>
The fish burritos were very flavorful (better than the tacos). The guacamole was bland and there was a sticker from the avocado in mine. It shows it is made fresh, which also means the guacamole today may be different. They should sell the chipotle sauce. Would have loved to bring a bottle home of that. Line seems to be really long on the weekends during meal times but it was moving at a decent pace.

Update: Love their baja fish tacos.  One of the family's favorite places to go for tacos, especially when taking a walk in Downtown Encinitas.  Still not impressed by their guacamole.  It is not bad, but not special - good price though.  There is not much seating for how busy they are.  Still love the chipotle sauce.  Cilantro sauce is very good as well.< /text>

<Review>This restaurant was disappointing. It is very similar to one in la Jolla but I recommend the one in la Jolla better. So... the food was okay I guess. It was somewhat flavorless and I had other issues with this restaurant. First off... after ordering they took a very long time to get me my food. I forgot to order something and I went back and placed a second order much later and the strange thing is that we received my second order first. After almost finishing my food from the second order my original first order finally arrived. Now my second order where fish tacos. The first order where carne assada tacos. It didn't seem like a super night but it was a little busy after we arrived. There were about four cooks and a waiter. And I will get to my second complaint about the waiter in a moment. The fish and shrimp tacos were okay but I did not like the idea of cheese in it. So what they did was grill the tortilla with cheese that melted and got hard on the tortilla. with the flavor of the cheese over powering the whole taco. now I've never been to a place where they put cheese in carne asada tacos. The carne asada was more like huge chunks of steak. Again that is not carne asada. And you don't especially cut it in that manner for tacos. The food looks fresh and good but it's just doesn't taste right and fit well with me. Now, the handling of the food by the waiter was somewhat disgusting as my wife observed him touching everything from cleaning tables trash and then the food without any gloves. First of all the waiter/ server should not be touching the food. In this restaurant, it is in the process of how the cook passes the food on to the server to garnish and prep the plate but he should not be physically touching the food. And what made disgusted was that he was cleaning table picking up trash and then handling the food with his bare hands. The reason I gave it to stars is for the effort of authenticity but this restaurant needs to correct a lot of issues and problems. with some corrections and modifications this restaurant could easily be a four to five star rating. I can see why it has so many high ratings and to me it seems that a lot of the inebriated people from the neighboring bars come and eat here late night and think they're getting a great meal. That brings up another point as well, you don't really want to bring kids here at night. I came with my 5-6-year-olds and teenagers and is not the kind of place for a family. People are intoxicated and this one woman was wearing a mini skirt if you want to call it that and nothing else under that.. Again two stars only for the effort of the restaurant but they really need to improve at least on their food handling procedure.< /Review><pics>None<//pics><response>None< /response><GmapID>0x80dc0c422d86fd41:0x56738be51e31f070< /GmapID></record>

< Review>
glad to make this my first review!!! Always walked by this place and noticed the long line, almost 20-30 people long almost everyday. Line looks deceiving, I waited about 15-20 minutes tops. WELL WORTH THE WAIT!!! The shrimp Tacos and the carne sada fries are probably the best I have ever had, equivalent to those late night Taco runs I use to make after a late night of drinking. Shrimp was fresh and the carne sada was extremely great and perfect quality. Not greasy at all and the whole set up inside was great. Just remember it is first come first serve on seating, so be on your toes to catch a seat!!! Oooo yeah, it is also fairly priced too!!!<//Review>

<text>I read over the weekend that The Taco Stand was rated one of the best taco restaurants in California.  I was going to be in Carlsbad so I decided to stop by and grab dinner on my way home.  I was able to find parking right in front at around 4:15 on Sunday and there was no line when I walked in.  This changed, by 4:30 the line was out the door.  I ordered 2 baja tacos (no tomato) and 1 carne asada.  I don't generally order carne asada tacos however the article I read said this was very flavorful carne asada.  I unfortunately had to order to go, since my son was with me and is not a taco lover. I did however open a baja taco before I drove away.  The taco was wonderful. The tortilla was fresh, hot and fluffy.  The fish was perfectly fried, nice and crisp and wonderful flavor. Everything about the taco was fresh.  I decided to eat the carne asada second just in case it didn't live up to the hype.  The carne asada was seasoned very well and cooked perfectly.  The tortilla again was perfect.  This is one of the best carne asada tacos I have had.  I elected to wait until I got home to eat my last baja taco as I had already eaten two while driving.  When arrived home about 20 minutes later, my taco was still fresh and tasted great.

I had also ordered some chips and ate chips with some of their great sauces they had at the salsa bar.  Nothing about this taco shop disappointed.  The food was wonderful and the service was great.  I'd happily visit again.< /text>< pictures>

<Rate>1< /Rate><Text>Almost any other night, a Taco Stand Surf n' Turf burrito with a side of guac and their usual staff would easily pull down 4 stars, but tonight one staffer dragged our experience right down to the gutter. After we claimed our meal from the counter, my wife, 16 month old toddler and I found the only empty seat in the entire restaurant, which happened to be on the patio. As we were taking our seats, a man who I gathered was the manager exclaimed that the patio was closed and pointed us in the direction of the door. Without any irony, he used the return motion of pointing us away to plop his burrito right on our table to begin his meal. As we made our way to the inside dining area, I took notice of a sign on the sliding glass door saying "Patio closes @ 9:30pm". OK, I thought, no harm no foul then... until I checked my watch and it read 9:05. I don't believe one bad actor should bring down the rating of an overall good establishment, but what he did could have been handled A LOT better, especially given there was zero seats indoors. The next time I have a GREAT experience I will revisit this rating and star them accordingly.</Text><userid>117191366070735639780< /userid>< date>

< Rate>
4</Rate>
<text>If you're into beach vacations, the Hilton San Diego/Del Mar isn't a bad option. It's about a 25 Lyft ride from the airport just north of San Diego several blocks from the ocean. It's a large property with a bar, restaurant, breakfast area, gym, etc. Once you check-in at the lobby, you'll be guided outside to your room. The rooms are all flanking the outdoor pool and hot tub.

The rooms themselves are large. The bathrooms are spacious with a separate room for the toilet within the bathrooms. If you're traveling with a baby, there's more than enough space for a crib (that the hotel will provide). If you want a room with a view, ask for it to face the pool and not the parking lot.

Two things to note: 1) The hotel is clearly old and it has that musky, beach hotel smell throughout, including your room. 2) The cleaning staff are friendly, but not attentive. Every day I was there, I had to ask for them to clean my room and my room was never fully cleaned afterwards.< /text>< pics>
None< /pics>

<Resp>None</Resp><Review>I first discovered these guys years ago in La Jolla and now enjoy go to the Encinitas spot when I go to my local beach, Moonlight.

Line was long, but not as long as it can get. If you can endure the wait their food is always worth it. My wife and I usually split a Mar y Tierra burrito and eat it with plenty of their Chipotle mayo sauce.

Despite the large number of people they are serving as fast as they can, the shrimp and steak wet cooked to perfection. This is one of my top five favorite restaurants in San Diego.

Also the have this new cilantro mayo sauce which is also amazing.

I almost don't want to recommend this place as I would love to keep it to myself, but one look at how busy they ALWAYS are and you know the has been out of the bag for a long time.< /Review></record>

< Text>
The food and atmosphere is awful. Staff was OK, no complaints there. If I could rate just the staff, it would be 4/5.

The patio smelled like rotten garbage, which was only minimally worse than the food tasted. Salsas are mostly cream sauces which werent good at all. The chicken looked and tasted like pork. Carne Asada fries were bland and boring. How do you make bland guacamole? You have to work at removing the avocado flavor to do that.

The tables have 4 legs at the corners instead of one in the middle like a normal place, so in order to sit on the bench seats (the only thing open) we had to move the table out to sit down.

0/10 would eat here again.</Text>

There was a line out the door when we arrived in Encinitas so we took note and decided to give it a try.  We were not disappointed.  Everything made fresh to order.  Al pastor burrito was STUFFED with meat.  Fish tacos were good.  Chips and guac was amazing... so much avocado.  Free refills on Jamaica and horchata made the kids happy. < review>
BEST Mexican flavor in San Diego!
The Taco Stand, makes Mexican food right, only place where I have seen tacos al pastor done the right way.
Their salsas, with thw exception of the cilantro salsa which is very "Californian-Mex" are done with an authenticity flair.
The corn on the cob, pure Mexican style!
You must try the guacamole, it truly looks and taste like homemade!
Very pleasant surprise in a town full of fake Mexican food like Bandini's or Chipotle.
A MUST!<//review>

< Text>
It used to be good but since last time I wrote a review(you can read the old one below) a lot changed.
Orderes over the app and payed. Got there no food. They didnt even started no apologies or anything. The lady who was making the food did put just a drop of guacamole in there. I called her on it....nothing just look at me funny.
And the biggest issue i have is the meat qualitty used to be really good... not anymore.
I use to send anyone I know to that place.
Not anymore.

Awesome food . I have been their twice and  I tried their California burrito and el pastor tacos. Taste wise amazing, they do have tasty salsa bar as well. Price point is pretty good for enci.
I would have given them five stars if they had their order processing somehow together. the reason why they have long lines is not only because of the good food. There is only one cashier which handles phone orders and helping people in the line and she is not the fastest either.
I suggest to order over the phone if you want to take out.< /Text>

<user_name>Bret Londer< /user_name>< date>
1491505454829<//date>
<rate>5<//rate><review>I dug this place. There aren't many restaurants in Encinitas that my wife and I haven't tried, so when this opened up, we were chomping at the bit to give it a shot. We skipped it the first few attempts because there was always a long line out of the door. Useful tip: The register is right by the front door, so only 2-3 people can actually be in line before it's out the door. Do not fear a line as it will move quickly.

The menu has the right amount of options on it, and some of my favorites (al pastor) are there. They even have lengua and menudo on the weekends, so you can get your authentic Mexican noms here. Prices are good. Seating can be a little chaotic as the process is that you order, sit, and then get your food when they shout that it's ready. I'm attributing some of this to their busy-ness and newness, but it wasn't easy to find a clean table. We snagged a dirty one right as our food was coming out, but I was moderately concerned that we were going to have to stand and eat.

We'll definitely be back as there are several other items on the menu that I want to try.<//review>< pics>
None<//pics>

None< /Resp>
